segments.text: were regarded rather highly.
Yeah, Scripp Mitchell was, he was a drawing teacher.
I enjoyed him.
He was a fine old gentleman.
Colonel R.T. Milner, he was a
I was a native of Henderson and was a friend of my mother and father.
He was president at that time.
He was president all the time you were there, I believe, was he not?
Did you have much personal contact with him?
Very little.
Very little, even though he was a family friend.
That's right.
I didn't want to be accused of polishing the apple.
Uh-huh.
Well, I could see where that might be a problem.
Yeah.
What was the overall attitude, would you say, of the students to President Milner on one hand and also to the commandant on the other hand?
That would be the total university administration.
Well, they liked Colonel Milner.
They liked Captain Moses.
But Levi and Gene Brown, they didn't think so much of.
He was the commandant the last year or so you were there.
What was the problem with Mr. Brown?
I guess he was just a little too, I don't know whether you'd call it strict or what, but the boys, they didn't like him as well as they did Captain Moses.
Captain Moses was a Texan to start with.
Was there a big age difference between Captain Moses and Mr. Brown?
Not too much.
Lieutenant Brown, he was the first lieutenant.
Was there a captain there?
Moses was the captain.
They had both been regular Army for a good while, though, I think.
Yes.
One of the things that's of a considerable amount of interest to us is the
numerous traditions which are carried on particularly in the Corps of Cadets today.
And we like to find out which of these were in vogue when you were a student.
Today we have such things as the silver taps, the muster, and the bonfire in particular.
and some other odds and ends.
Were any of these in existence at the time you were there?
No, we never had a bonfire, and we never had silver taps, and we never had a muster during my time there.
Have you been to a muster since you graduated?
Not there.
I've been to it locally.
Yeah, locally.
Well, we had understood that
that the muster tradition began in 1903 when the Corps decided that Texas Independence Day should not be a school day and they need to have a holiday.
It seemed to me we had a holiday, but we didn't have a muster as such.
Well, they don't have a holiday today, but they have a muster.
Kind of reversed it there.
We know that from time to time, some of the faculty children, faculty, perhaps faculty wives or other faculty relatives, girls in particular, attended classes at A&M.
Were there any girls in classes while you were there?
Colonel Miller had a niece that, what was her name?
that attended some classes.
She lived with them and attended some classes.
Gieske's had two daughters that attended some classes.
What Gieske was that?
He was...
F.E.?
F.E., I guess.
Taught there, and he was later on, I believe...
He was in some phase of engineering, I don't know.
He was college engineer for a long, long time, I believe, and a college architect.
And he was in the... Well, now, wait a minute.
Must not have been F.E.
This gentleman had a Halliburton stash.
But F.E., if I'm thinking, no, I'm...
I'm thinking of another one, I guess.
If he was class of 88 or something like that.
He's probably the one.
The one I'm thinking about was class of 12, I believe.
I believe he had a son probably class of 12.
Yeah.
I've forgotten now what his name was.
Those are the only three that I recall.
I don't think we've covered this yet.
We know that there were
number of students who had jobs of one sort or another while they were there, and of course continue that practice today.
Did you have some type of student employment while you were there?
No.
Okay.
Yeah, we had all sorts of...
I used to be over at the experimental station.
He had the newspaper, Houston Post, I believe it was.
He delivered it on campus or something?
He subscribed to it and he delivered it.
What was his name?
Having gone through school and been in the Corps of Cadets and having attained the rank of captain the time you graduated, did you participate in the First World War then after you graduated?
Yes.
In what capacity did you serve?
Well, I tried to get in everything I could, and I had flat feet, and they turned me down.
I finally went to San Antonio while I was working in San Antonio.
And a friend of mine who, I was working for the Bell Telephone Company, and a friend of mine who was with the Bell Telephone, in fact, I moved to San Antonio to take his place.
He had gotten into the Signal Corps and got a commission right out of Civil Life, and he told me about it, so I went out.
The doctor that examined me all he noticed was that thumb.
I sprained that wrist one time, and that's all I could do with that thumb was do it like that.
I couldn't straighten it out to save my neck that way.
He said, what's the matter with that thumb, son?
I said, nothing.
Wiggled it.
Well, I was in the Army.
I got a commission right out of the Civil Life, the Signal Corps.
And where all did you serve then?
You mean training and all?
Yeah, what, did you stay in the United States all the time or did you go abroad?
No, I went to what was then Camp Alfred Vale, Little Silver, New Jersey.
It's now Fort Monmouth there, Signal Corps' main training camp.
And from there I went to Fort Levmouth to a depot, which I ended up getting ready to go overseas.
Went overseas.
I first was a post signal officer at Bordeaux.
Then they transferred me to Nevers, and from Nevers to Trier in Germany after the armistice was signed, and from Trier to Paris, and from then back home.
Have any particular exciting experiences while you were there?
No, it was very calm.
I was an SOS all the time.
There was nothing exciting going on.
Okay.
If we might jump back to your student days again for a couple of minutes.
In looking through the Longhorns from your senior year, it had indication that you had sort of gone up the ranks in G Company.
but that you were also a first lieutenant in the RV.
How were you selected for the RV?
Well, they had a secret vote.
When I was there, you had to be voted on to get in.
There were no scholastic requirements when I was there.
How about military competence?
Well, yes.
That was a consideration, I'm sure.
Well, I know it was because I voted on plenty of them.
I thought you said you were in for how many years then?
I went in in the fall of my junior year.
We're in for junior and senior year.
So you participated in the two vote, two elections.
Who selected, I noticed you were first lieutenant in your senior year.
How were you chosen to be first lieutenant?
Voted on.
Within the members of the RV, they elected all of the officers.
Did being in the RV require a good bit more of your time than being in the regular corps of cadets?
No.
Just the drill.
The drill was the only additional time we spent.
We didn't devote any time to anything else.
We didn't make any trips like the RVs do now.
And there's this drill and exhibitions.
We had exhibitions, of course, but those were usually on Sundays.
Uh-huh.
For whom would you have the exhibition?
Oh, some dignitary that might come to school.
Well, this would be the commandant would ask you to ask the RVs to give a demonstration.
You were then kind of the crack drill team.
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
OK.
You were also a member, if you can remember this, of something referred to as the KK.
Yeah.
What did those initials stand for?
Keelakinesis.
K-E-L-A-K-E-N-K-E-N-E-S-I-S, I guess.
And what was the function of that?
It was a dance club, strictly a dance club.
What kind of dances?
Or dancing?
Oh, ballroom dances all they ever did back in those days.
Didn't do square dancing?
No, no.
It was near a fraternity, I guess you could say.
Did this organization sponsor dances for the students?
No, just for the club.
Just for the club.
How frequently did you have a dance?
About two a year.
And who would do the music?
Who would provide the music?
We'd bring in orchestras.
Bring in an orchestra.
How large of an organization was it then?
20 members.
So you would then, with that small a membership, unless you had somebody to supply you with some money, you couldn't have brought in very much of a big-name orchestra then, I take it.
Well, I don't know how they did it, I don't recall, but I know I chipped in and we paid to have orchestras come in.
Of course, we know none of these big-name orchestras.
Not like for the senior hop or something like that?
No, no.
Commencement hop.
Any idea how old the organization was by the time you joined it?
No, but I know that was supposed to be the end of it.
13 was supposed to be the end of it.
13 was the end of it.
Was that by a decision?
We were more or less sub Rosa my senior year.
Was that the decision of the school then?
Yeah, the school authorities.
It got to be a little political down there between the Swastikas and the KKs.
Who were the Swastikas?
That was another organization like the KKs.
For dances?
Well, it was a dance club originally, but it got so political that they, oh, I won't say this.
Some of my old Swastika friends might hear this.
They didn't have a limited membership, I'll put it that way.
So they had a larger membership.
They had a larger membership than the KKs, yeah.
And were you elected as a KK?
How about the Swastikas?
Were you elected to that too?
But it was not as strict on who went in?
Well, I don't know.
We had certain requirements.
I don't recall just exactly what they were.
You had to be a decent type fellow.
No financial requirements.
You didn't have to be from rich parents or anything of that sort.
Just kind of like getting into a fraternity, I'd say.
And where did the girls come from for the dances that you had?
All over the country.
Oh, did you bring your girl from home primarily?
Did any of the fellows have girls from Bryan to come for the dances?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yeah.
What about any of the faculty daughters?
Well...
As I recall, there weren't any other there than the Gieske two daughters that were that age.
So that kind of limited that.
Yes.
There was a girl from Brown married the Texas University coach that used to coach it then.
The Bible?
The Bible, the ex-Bible.
Rowena Rose, she was what we called a college widow.
And there was a girl named Brian, Dessie Weddington, and Madeline Hanway, who was Madeline Parker, and there was a slew of Brian girls.
But they imported them.
I imported one from Brian, from Beaumont all the time.
The Longhorn also indicated you were manager of the Turnverein.
Turnverein Club, yes.
That was a club inside just an athletic club in the NG Company.
We had room in the basement of Goodwin Hall, and we converted it into a gymnasium.
We had boxing clubs and a punching bag.
dumbbells and inning clubs and things like that.
So what, you kind of took care of the equipment as manager of it?
Yeah.
Was this a common practice for... No, that's the only club of that type on the campus.
Was the only one of that like that on campus?
Did you just have a larger percentage of athletically inclined men in your company?
No, I think we had a fellow named Clyde Griesenbeck that was
athletically inclined.
He didn't play football, baseball, or track or anything else, but he liked to keep the condition.
And he formed that little club.
Yeah, I imagine that was a fairly short-lived thing.
It was in that one year.
And then you said, I believe, you were manager of the basketball team.
Yeah, that was A&M's first basketball team, too.
What was your responsibility there?
Well, take care of the equipment and, well, there wasn't much of anything to do other than that.
But you made all the trips with the team.
Made all the trips and looked after the finances of getting the money in.
Of course, we played Houston High School and Galveston High School and the Galveston YMCA.
That's about all the teams that were available.
Those are the only two trips we made, one to Houston and one to Galveston.
Then did you play some games on campus, too?
Oh, yes.
We played the high school, I don't recall.
I believe we played the YMCA, Galveston YMCA on campus.
Well, Monty Montgomery, he was a football player and a basketball player.
I guess the star of that team.
Gosh, when you get old as I am, names kind of slip away from you.
I know what you mean.
I'm somewhat younger than you are, and lots of names have slipped away from me.
But Zeke Caldwell, whose father had a jewelry store in Bryan,
There's still a Caldwell's Jewelry in Bryan.
Is there?
You graduated in the spring of 13.
What did you do as your first job after you graduated?
Well, I lived in San Angelo and my father had sold the ranch.
Wasn't anything to do.
I didn't want to be a cowboy.
So I went to Dallas and
Ran into a former Aggie, worked for Bell Telephone Company, and got a job with them in the traffic department.
Became a traffic chief, what they called a traffic chief, and worked on through to the latter part of the 17.
I was made Division Supervisor of Traffic at San Antonio, and that's when I got in the Army.
What have you done, what did you do after you got out of the Army then?
Oh, I got into the oil business down in the Eastland, Rangers, this and that.
And what aspect of the oil business did you get into?
Production.
Production.
Had a lease down near Ranger and also was in sales for a while.
For how long did you do that?
I'd say four or five years.
What did you do next then?
I went to work for the Federal Land Bank of Houston.
The Farm Credit Administration signed with the Federal Land Bank of Houston.
At what point?
Do you remember what year that was?
Where were you located first?
here, Lubbock.
You come directly to Lubbock in 1933 then, with the Federal Land Bank out of Houston.
And you were in what capacity, an appraiser?
Land Bank appraiser was the title.
What was your, what did you do?
Appraised farms and ranches for loans.
This would be if somebody wanted to buy the farmland?
Well, various purposes.
They had
They'd make loans for purchase of property, for improvement of property.
And if you had something above a homestead, you could get money to buy cattle or equipment.
You say something above a homestead?
Yeah.
200 acres is a suburban homestead.
So if you had more than 200 acres?
More than 200 acres, yeah.
You could borrow money to buy cattle or equipment.
They've liberalized that a lot since I left.
Of course you can't borrow in Texas, you can't create a loan on a homestead for anything other than purchase money or improvements.
You can't borrow money on a homestead to buy livestock or invest in something else.
But say, if you own more than 200 acres, but you don't live there, you can borrow money on it then, I take it.
If it's not your place of residence.
Well, let's say you own a section of land.
You can cut off your homestead and borrow on the excess.
Uh-huh.
320 acres.
You can cut off 120 acres and borrow on that.
So for how long did you...
worked for the Federal Land Bank then?
Well, from 33 to 61.
That's... Nearly 30 years.
You're 29.
I'm 29, yes.
And you retired?
Yeah.
I've had my own appraisal and loan service since that time.
You work pretty steadily, or do you kind of work when you want to?
When I want to.
I might work two or three cases a year, something like that.
Now, how long a time would it, you say two or three cases, how much time would you put in on an individual case?
Well, it depends on the size of it, of course.
A farm, nominal size farm, would take from three to six, eight days.
The ranch might take you a month.
So since 61, then, you've been an appraiser.
Are you gradually decreasing the amount of appraising you do?
Well, that and I guess I'm not actively making loans anymore.
I just quit that.
I don't know.
I had a heart attack in 68, so that slowed me down.
That slowed you down a good bit, yeah.
I was real active up until then, but since then I've slowed down considerably.
You say you quit making loans, and were you...
I was soliciting loans.
I broker a loan, put it that way.
In other words, you would act as a go-between between somebody who wanted to borrow money and somebody who had something to lend.
Yeah.
I represented the Prudential Insurance Company and Equitable Life Insurance Society.
Those people would be interested in loaning fairly substantial amounts of money, I believe.
Oh, yeah.
They didn't have any limit to their loans.
Did they have a minimum limit?
Oh, it seemed to me like $2,500 was the least that they could.
Normally it was $5,000.
They didn't have a loan under that.
Because it costs money to put loans on a book, you know, and service them.
So you've got to have a good enough interest return to pay that.
Uh-huh.
Had you had any contact with any of these insurance companies previously for you to get started becoming a loan solicitor for them?
Oh, yes.
We appraised them.
We hobnobbed with representatives of different companies.
This was when you were an appraiser with the land bank.
With the land bank, yes.
I'm not a reprobate.
I've been an elder in the Presbyterian Church for 40 years.
I'd like to get that in there.
Okay.
We do want to record any other service you've done to the community.
Well, being a land bank appraiser, I was in the country all the time.
I do belong to Kiwanis Club now, and I have in time belonged to Rotary Club and Alliance Club.
over the years, but until I retired, I didn't try to belong to any service club or take any active part in civic affairs.
You might step back for a minute in your time with the land bank to ask how wide of an area did you cover when you were an appraiser?
Well, when I worked at the land bank, I usually say I worked all
Well, from north Texas, from Temple north, and from east and west, from El Paso to Louisiana and Oklahoma line.
So you covered almost the entire state.
Yeah.
Since I retired, I've worked practically all of Texas and a good part of New Mexico.
So you had a good bit of traveling to do.
Yeah, I did.
I was going home so much that I couldn't belong to a service club.
Well, the land bank had appraisers in other areas.
Oh, yeah.
In fact, there was another one here in Lubbock.
One in Plainview, one in Amarillo.
They had quite a bit of loan business.
How would they determine who would go to a particular location to appraise a piece of property?
Well, when I first started, they would assign all the applications to one individual, and he would, in turn, he was in charge of a group of appraisers.
That was in 1933 when they
the Farm Loan Act went into effect in a big way.
That is, they put on another 25% that they could loan and call it the commissioner loan.
Farmers were all in terrible condition, and financially, you know.
Insurance companies were pressing them.
All lenders, all institutional lenders were really after them to pay off if they could.
And this leader of the group would pass out the applications.
Later, they got to signing them from the bank.
I remember one weekend, just before Christmas, I was down at Steamboat.
And the chief appraiser called me and told me that
He was going to send me the next week way up in Follett, way up in the very northeast part of Texas, up in Lipscomb County.
And I told him, I said, well, I'm going to stop home Christmas.
You know that, don't you?
He said, oh, yes, I'm sure.
But they sent us all over.
They wanted us to go.
Later, they...

The last two or three years, three or four years, the amount of time they assigned them, they let the Secretary of Treasuries assign me, the managers of these farm owners associations, to sign the applications.
At that time we had a territory, but there was overlap on that.
Wasn't that a hard and fast rule, staying either within a given territory?
